<paragraph blockId="12.[151,684,725,973]" pageId="12" pageNumber="89">
ECOLOGY. — Forest at low elevation (
<quantity metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" metricValueMax="5.0" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="12" pageNumber="89" unit="m" value="300.0" valueMax="500.0" valueMin="100.0">100- 500 m</quantity>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="89" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,684,725,973]" pageId="12" pageNumber="89">
DISTRIBUTION. — Most collections are from the area around the Baie d'Antongil; one sterile collection provisionally placed here is from Andilanatoby, much further south. — 
<figureCitation box="[569,639,883,909]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="7.[152,182,1095,1112]" captionTargetBox="[164,642,175,1060]" captionTargetId="figure-460@7.[164,644,167,1060]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Fig. 3. — Distribution of Beilschmiedia microphylla (*); B. moratii (✚); B. opposita (Δ); B. rugosa (•); B. sary ()." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5180985" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5180985/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="89">Fig. 3.</figureCitation>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,684,725,973]" pageId="12" pageNumber="89">PHENOLOGY. — Flowers in September; fruits in December.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="89" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,684,1011,1343]" pageId="12" pageNumber="89">
<taxonomicName box="[177,368,1011,1038]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Lauraceae" genus="Beilschmiedia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Laurales" pageId="12" pageNumber="89" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sary">
<emphasis box="[177,368,1011,1038]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="89">Beilschmiedia sary</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[515,631,1011,1036]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Lauraceae" genus="Beilschmiedia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Laurales" pageId="12" pageNumber="89" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="opposita">
<emphasis box="[515,631,1011,1036]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="89">B. opposita</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but is larger and coarser, growing at lower elevation and with a noticeably raised reticulate venation on both leaf surfaces. The inflorescences are as small as in 
<taxonomicName box="[271,385,1134,1159]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Lauraceae" genus="Beilschmiedia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Laurales" pageId="12" pageNumber="89" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="opposita">
<emphasis box="[271,385,1134,1159]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="89">B. opposita</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; the flowers of 
<taxonomicName box="[553,623,1134,1159]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Lauraceae" genus="Beilschmiedia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Laurales" pageId="12" pageNumber="89" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sary">
<emphasis box="[553,623,1134,1159]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="89">B. sary</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
seem to lack staminodia representing Whorl IV, while the stamens of Whorl III are poorly developed and likely sterile. However, only one flowering specimen with few flowers is known. The tepals are deciduous in older flowers exactly as in 
<emphasis box="[151,272,1318,1343]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="89">
<taxonomicName box="[151,268,1318,1343]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Lauraceae" genus="Beilschmiedia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Laurales" pageId="12" pageNumber="89" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="opposita">B. opposita</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[177,454,1382,1409]" box="[177,454,1382,1409]" pageId="12" pageNumber="89">COMMON NAME. — Sary.</paragraph>
